\begin_layout Section
Scanning probe microscopy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scanning probe microscopy (SPM) is a series of techniques to produce detailed
 images over a 3D surface.
 A sharp tip is moved across the surface and the scan of surface-tip interaction
s form a map of those interactions.
 Piezoelectric crystals let the tip move in all directions over short distances
 with fine precision.
 Additional motors, such as a stepper motor, can move the entire piezoelectric
 crystal and tip structure over larger distances but sacrifice precision.
 With an isolated environment, engineered to shield the tip from external
 noise, and a sharp tip, the SPM map can provide details down to the atomic
 level.
 There are many different types of SPM that measure quantities like magnetic
 field, density of states, and spin; far too many to discuss here, so only
 a brief overview of the most relevant are below.
\end_layout

