\begin_inset Formula $\sim200nm$
\end_inset

 thick coating.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lorand"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Finally we bake it at 
\begin_inset Formula $180C$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $60s$
\end_inset

 on a hot plate to remove some solvent.
 Next a layer of SPR-3012 is dynamically dispensed at 900RPM.
 The substrate is then sped up and spun again at 
\begin_inset Formula $4000RPM$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $45s$
\end_inset

 flattening the SPR-3012 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1.3\mu m$
\end_inset

 thick.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "megaposit"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 This is then baked for 
\begin_inset Formula $95C$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $60s$
\end_inset

 on a hot plate.
 The resist stack and flake is then exposed using a MA/BA Gen4 or Gen2 Contact
 Aligner (SUSS MicroTec) with 54mW of light.
 The patterned resist is then developed for 
\begin_inset Formula $60s$
